{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514195"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.68,0.1,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4814"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63343"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7726"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman is brought in to the emergency department after a road traffic crash in which she sustained multiple abdominal and head injuries. On examination, her blood pressure is 90/70mmHg, pulse rate 128/min and temperature 36.8\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She is opening her eyes in pain, withdrawing her limbs from pain and making incomprehensible sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is her score according to the Glasgow coma scale?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["E3, M4, V2","E2, M4, V2","E2, M2, V3","E1, M3, V1","E2, M3, V3"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario has a total GCS score of 8, with divisions as \u003Cstrong\u003EE2, M4, V2\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient is opening her eyes only on pain (E2), withdrawing only on pain (M4) and saying incomprehensible sounds (V2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE3, M4, V2 \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be a GCS score or a person who will open eyes on speech, withdraw limbs from pain and is saying incomprehensible sounds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE2, M2, V3 \u003C/strong\u003Ewould consist of a patient opening their eyes to the pain, giving only an extensor response and saying inappropriate words.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE1, M3, V1\u003C/strong\u003E would be a patient who is not opening their eyes, giving an abnormal flexion response and not giving a verbal response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE2, M3, V3\u003C/strong\u003E would consist of a patient opening their eyes to the pain, giving an abnormal flexion response and saying inappropriate words.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe GCS score is divided into three categories, mild (13-15), moderate (9-12), and severe (3-8). An initial score of less than 5 is associated with an 80% chance of being in a lasting vegetative state or death. An initial score of greater than 11 is associated with 90% chance of recovery. The lowest GCS score that a patient can have is 3 which is associated with severe mortality and is consider imminent brain death in a case of traumatic brain injury, a score of 15 on GCS scale is the best and means that the patient is fully conscious and can be safely discharge after treating their symptoms . Generally a GCS score of 8 or less necessitates intubation but it is not necessarily enforced in every hospital guidelines and should be used as a guide to asses patient and decide whether intubation is necessary or not. GCS score is used to describe patient\u0027s level of consciousness in all medical and surgical situations but the outcomes vary from case to case, for example a GCS score of 3 in a patient with drug overdose is not necessarily associated with severe mortality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A patient with eyes opening on pain, limb withdrawing on pain and saying incomprehensible sounds have a GCS score of E2, M4, V2.","The Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) is a tool used to assess a patient\u0027s level of consciousness after a head injury.","A GCS score of 8 or less is considered severe and may necessitate intubation."],"references":["J.P Leach, R.J. Davenport. Neurological disease. In: Davidson\u0027s Principles and Practice of Medicine . 22nd ed. New Delhi, Punjab: Elsevier Ltd.; 2014. p. 1160\u2013.","Li A, Atem FD, Venkatachalam AM, Barnes A, Stutzman SE, Olson DM. Admission Glasgow Coma Scale Score as a Predictor of Outcome in Patients Without Traumatic Brain Injury. Am J Crit Care. 2021 Sep 1;30(5):350-355. doi: 10.4037/ajcc2021163. PMID: 34467380. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34467380/","Jain S, Iverson LM. Glasgow Coma Scale. 2023 Jun 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30020670. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30020670/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63343"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18488"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18488"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3d735632-8cd0-4651-a4c9-ea384dcdb5fa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3d735632-8cd0-4651-a4c9-ea384dcdb5fa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":844}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63343"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T12:50:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T12:52:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4814"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77822"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagno